    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-10-11T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-10-11T11:00:00-05:00" n="312"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d312">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00R296/5870: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-10-11T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >October 11, 1934—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 11—2:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>196. Your 120, October 9, 6 p.m. I presented <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi>
                    to State Secretary Bülow today. He read me telegram sent Luther yesterday to the
                    effect that Germany hoped all creditor nations would agree to reduction interest
                    rate and that special note issue in the nature of register marks was being
                    arranged to the end that bondholders might obtain their full interest. Pending
                    receipt of further particulars I remain skeptical as to whether such an issue
                    could perform this purpose, remove discrimination involved by payment of other
                    countries in cash or avoid depressing still further the existing market for
                    register marks. As usual on such occasions the question of trade negotiations
                    with the United States was raised and Bülow, whose attitude throughout seemed
                    most conciliatory, agreed that if these should come about the barriers to
                    American commerce raised by Germany would have to be relaxed.</p>
                <p>I also raised question of discrimination against American shipping mentioned in
                    your 121, October 10, 6 p.m.<note n="71" xml:id="d312fn71">
                        <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_447">p. 447</ref>.</note>
                    Bülow was not familiar with the matter and promised prompt investigation.
                    Consulate General, which has handled this matter, finds that decree is not
                    discriminatory as far as the text is concerned but that its application will
                    probably prove so. Consulate General recommends that North Atlantic Conference
                    rule that all freights from the United States to Germany be prepaid in advance
                    so that all German importers would be compelled to include in their original
                    application for currency cost of ocean freight and other incidental charges (see
                    Consulate General despatch No. 2210, October 6,<note n="72" xml:id="d312fn72"
                        >Not printed.</note> due Washington early next week).</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dodd</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
